===Etymology===
From {{etyl|frm|en}} {{m|frm|pragmatique}}, from {{etyl|LL.|en}} {{m|la|pragmaticus||relating to civil affair; in Latin, as a noun, a person versed in the law who furnished arguments and points to advocates and orators, a kind of attorney}}, from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{m|grc|πραγματικός||active, versed in affairs}}, from {{m|grc|πρᾶγμα||a thing done, a fact}}, in plural {{m|grc|πράγματα||affairs, state affairs, public business, etc.}}, from {{m|grc|πράσσειν||to do}} (whence English {{m|en|practical}}).

